      \field{abstract}{The transmission of sound in stored grain was investigated to facilitate the use of sensitive microphones to detect insect infestations. Such infestations cause significant loss (about 10\%, or a billion (109) dollars worth, annually in the USA), and early detection is an important factor in reducing such losses. The tests were conducted in a tank containing about 5 m3 of wheat. The phase velocity of sound and the absorption coefficient were measured as a function of frequency using a two-channel analyzer system. Data were analyzed using sound-transmission theory in porous media. It is shown that sound is transmitted principally through the air passages between the grains and that, over a distance of 1 m, grain is highly absorbing at frequencies above about 1 kH. The theory provides a measure of the average spacing between grains, which at a depth of 0.5 m was found to be about 0.6 mm.}
